<font color="#FF0000">GO EASY, BROTHER CHRIS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar 15 13:33:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chris, for a guy who takes obvious pleasure in his own<br>
logic, literacy, and maturity, you certainly digressed<br>
into a petty rage when any aspect of your philosophy was<br>
called into doubt. How dare this &quot;Old Man&quot; question the<br>
veracity of an ideologue's platitudes. Name calling is<br>
such fun, huh?<br><br>
Your points have validity, but much of it implies we can<br>
simply disarm the world and our kinder nature will take<br>
over. We live in a world of wolves and lambs and all in<br>
between. It implies the simple hard working engineer who's<br>
career with a company who manufactures military weapons,<br>
has mispent his life. He probably works there because it<br>
is the best job he could find to provide for his family. Shall we just trash him and his kind as well? What evil<br>
does he represent? Oh wait, my logic fails me; it's his<br>
boss, or maybe his Senator, or perhaps the electorate.<br><br>
This &quot;Old Man&quot; (which I am damn proud to be by the way.<br>
Since 1967-68 my years have been extra gravy. Fate could<br>
have selected me for one of those silver coffins easily<br>
enough) is a cynic, optimist, and prance around everywhere<br>
in between. One thing my milage has provided me, is<br>
a thick skin. If you want to zing me for questioning the<br>
eternal truth of peace and love, please do.<br><br>
War has provided us Vets with one very basic insight. We<br>
have seen and participated in Man's inhumanity to Man.<br>
American's are no more or less capable of War than any<br>
other human. The nobility of stopping Hitler was executed<br>
with the slaughter of hundreds of thousands of &quot;innocent&quot;<br>
people, but did the end justify the means? If you had been<br>
one of few Jewish, Dutch, or all the other groups being<br>
slaughtered by Nazi's, the end of that inhumanity seemed<br>
obvious. The WWII vets got to tote that tab. On both sides.<br><br>
On the other hand, I guess our &quot;slaughter&quot; of the Vietnamese<br>
was not justifiable since our purpose was awry. Tough luck<br>
for us Nam Vets, Huh? And what about those traditionally<br>
peace loving Vietnamese, who by the way were quite efficient<br>
at slaughtering each other for a couple of thousand years<br>
before we joined the fray. <br><br>
Bottom line. War is an empty unthinkable way to resolve<br>
conflicts between nations. On the other hand, we are a<br>
species of nationalists. That's what made Dr. King's<br>
speech of all people being as one was so inspiring to<br>
anyone. Beautiful in simplicity, but short on any reality<br>
that can be seen in the foreseeable future. Sad but true.<br><br>
No one is going to disagree with the philosophy you point<br>
out that we must continue to strive to move to a more<br>
peaceful and kind society. Even an old cynic like me dreams<br>
of a generation without war. But reality is just that,<br>
reality. Your angry reaction to my comments hints that your<br>
nature doesn't always jive with your intent, just like all<br>
the rest of the world.<br><br>
Keep the comments coming, but please, save the indignity.<br>
I'm not your enemy. Yes, I am old I guess. At 31, your<br>
no kid either. I look forward to more of your insight, and<br>
I really mean that.<br><br>
  <br><br>

